urtyard. But then there were - extra bits, and - newer bits. And - in the archway there was a - a doorway into the house each side you see. I'll try and describing - going in by the left, you'd have gone into a small hall - then there - a library - a big 
l
ibrary, I mean - rather lovely. Then you came to a very big hall, with the - big staircase going up to the next floor. Called the - South Hall. From there you went into the great hall. Which was a huge room. And I think it originally had big doors to whic
h
 probably, you know, coach - the coach drove up, but in our day it wasn't used as a door at all, all that was shut up. And that was only used for - parties. Then you came again into the absolute duplicate of the other hall called the North Hall. With a st
a
ircase up to the floor again - up - next floor. Then there was a - the - oak parlour, and - and - a room exactly the same size which was the small dining room. And then the very - and then a very big - dining room. And from the back of the very big dining
 room you started you see getting into the back premises, and into another - wing of the house, the later wing of the house. Downstairs, what was called the - the bachelors row. Rooms for - bachelors in fact, for your -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Bachelor guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Yes.
 I mean the least grand of the young - of the young men who came to stay - were put in the bachelors - room. And it also had - what do you call it where you keep the books - and - and papers?
