\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes, and - and stewards room. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Who ate in the stewards room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Butler. Cook. Cook. The house - the - housekeeper. A
nd - the lady's maid, and all the visiting ladies maids. And I suppose visiting - valet. Everybody else in the - and they were waited - I mean, they were waited on in the stewards room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Who would wait on them, one of the more junior ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I suppose - whether it was junior housemaid or junior - footmen I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But that sort of thing was something you didn't see very much of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. No. But I just know there was a stewards room apart from the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was there a brushing room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 O
h yes. And then there was a lamp room, because we had no electric light. And my father wouldn't put it in for some reason. Perhaps just economy, I don't know. We had moaning gas, in the passages. And - lamps, oil lamps - in all the rooms. So there were an
 enormous amount of them you see. And there was a special lamp man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was that his only job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I think so. I won't swear he had anything to do with the boots. He may have but I don't think so. I think he was just the lamp man. Oh no, I think he also 
dragged - an enormous sort of - truck like a - porters truck - with the food, because it was a long way from the - dining room - kitchen. I can - hear it; rumbling along stone passages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was the food usually cold by the time it got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I don't remember that, I - no, I don't think so. Somehow it was hot, I - suppose there was - hot arrangement on it. I don't think it was.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you know where your mother interviewed the housekeeper and gave her instructions and this kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I shou
ld think that she came - I don't know - either to her bedroom in the morning or to her sitting room. Don't think she went - to the housekeeper. I don't swear. She may have occasionally when - there was a place called the china room, where all the china - 
w
as kept, and I think occasionally she went there with her - if there was going to be a house party. There was tremendous arrangement about - what dinner service you had - for what meal, you know, and to vary them and - well I think they had - I believe we
 
did have - we did have a lot of very good china I believe. In fact I know from - sales after his brother - even my brothers sales - that we did have a lot of lovely china. And so according to who was coming, whether they appreciated china you know - we'll
 have such and such a dinner service out. And - for one night and another one the - the next night, so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Could you tell me something about your nurse, did you have the same one for a long time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. On no. Oh the same one for a long time but - 
we'd had - early ones whom I don't remember. Winding up with - a very brutal drunken one. When we were - at the time when we were in Ireland I was telling you and - my parents were away such a lot, and so they didn't know about it. It was only discovered 
through the Irish Factor eventually, about this terrible woman who used to - beat me, because I was so small. I was only two you see. And - knocked the nursery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 maids about. And was roaring drunk. So she was quickly sacked. And my mother said that - we must 
have a course of - spoiling - to get us over what we'd been through, you see, particularly me 'cos I'd - was terrified by then. And so she engaged a lady called Mrs. Flambard - old - nurse who'd been with one of her aunts in fact. And she was very kind an
d
 very comfortable, known to us as Barty, not nanny but Barty. Barty. And she was the old type - nurse of those days, I mean she wore - wonderful clothes. Splendid - satin dress on - Sundays and - which was ones great excitement and - beautiful little caps
. And what Barty's cap's going to be white lace with - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 Parma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
 violets, or was it going to be black lace with something else, with - black velvet bows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What did she wear during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 During the week I - think it was probably - some colour we th
ought duller you know, I should think sort of - grey poplin or grey silk, I mean not any sort of uniform, just a - a - bodice and skirt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 How long did she stay with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh she stayed - she stayed 'til my - brother was born. But she was really ge
tting rather - old to be a nanny then, and also my - mother - knew - that she would spoil him - so frightfully. She was quite a snob. That he was the little heir. And she knew that - he would be - but also she was - too - and he was delicate, and she was 
- wasn't really all that good on health I don't think. So she was - so she was then retired. Well, we went on seeing her, she lived 'til the - died during the 1914 war I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did she retire quite nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, she lived somewhere like Str
eatham or somewhere. We used to go and visit her there. We were - I mean we - were all in tears for - several weeks after she left. Because we were so attached to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did she tell you a lot about her childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, not much - not much. We - sur
rounded her with mystery. She had been born in Belgium and she was I think half - Belgian, Flambert I expect she was really, Flambart or something, and we wanted - and she - very vague about her parents. Probably - I should think she was illegitimate. But
 we - and we settled that, you know, that she was - illegitimate - royal father you know, illegitimate daughter of a - some tremendous swell, we - surrounded her with - glamour.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 How old do you think you were when you knew about children being illegitimate and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I suppose from Scott novels - got that fairly early, we where -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 And also from history too I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But she wasn't somebody who talked a great deal about the old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did she tell stories to you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I don't remember - her - her telling me fairy stories at all, she used to - read aloud - I think to me 'til I learnt to read, and - I think she told one stories about who she'd been with. The other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you remember feeling jealous about the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
No. Don't think so. No, 'cos the only one I remember her talking much about - you know, there was a - a cousin - called - Eddie Winterton, you may have remembered - read about him as a - politician. Wel
l he was - she was very fond of him but I mean - she didn't seem - she didn't make me jealous of him. She came from - to - to us from him I think. Recommended you see by my - great-aunt, his mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 How many nursery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 maids did she have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I should 
think when she first came only one. But then - oh well you see, when she came really I was her only charge. So I think it went on being one 'til my - brother was born. And then the short time she was - with him there was a - an under nurse, and a nursery}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 m
aid. For just - just for Jack. But - that's what my mother thought unnecessary, she thought - really no. A nurse and a nursery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 maid was all he wanted. Which - which was all he had afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 The nurse always ate with you did she, in the nursery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I used to eat with Barty.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 She didn't ever eat with the other servants at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. No. Oh no. Oh no, she was waited on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Who waited on her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Then again I think it was either housemaid - I - or - the under foot - the most under fo
otman. I think there was sometimes used to be either called school - or nursery - you know, did those - jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about the nursery maid, how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I should think when there was a nursery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 maid there she must have done it. But that I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did the house have a sort of suite of rooms which were for the children which were self-contained?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 At a - at Hornby. No, they were rather scattered I think really. 'Cos the nursery I remember on the ground floor. And our bedr
ooms were - miles away. And - schoolroom was - again - miles away. It was all scattered there. But - other places of course, like - Bordighera, when we had our villa there then it - everything was much more concentrated there. And that's I think what star
ted - one having - luncheon down, and I mean I used to lunch with the - family to Bordighera. Which meant I was about nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Before that you hadn't even lunched with them on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I suppose perhaps sometimes as a treat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But not often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. Things like Christmas I think and - but I don't think otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 When were you sort of promoted to the schoolroom out of the nursery, what kind of age was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well I never had a real - schoolroom, I never had a - resident governess. Well,
 never - anyhow for longer than a - a month of so. If parents away sometimes - I never did. It was - that was given up very early because - my mother - they had a - German - governess for my elder sisters, two eldest sisters, who my mother disliked so muc
h
 that she settled never to have a governess, a living in governess again. And after that I think we only had - only ones I remember living in were the - nursery - Swiss nursery governesses. Swiss nursery governesses and a very - advanced - sort of finishi
ng one for my - eldest sister who was - really more there as a com - companion to - read with, my sister was - frightfully delicate. And really - wasn't allowed ever to do very much. And she was there chiefly to read with her you know and - read to her.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was she a well educated woman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes, tremendously.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Can you remember what sort of things she read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh no, you see, because I wasn't - in on that, with - what she read with my sister. But - my sister was a tremendous reader. So that I -
 I don't know, I - I should think a good deal of art history. As I think - may have been a good deal of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Ruskin and people like that you think they would have read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. And - because I know that my - in Florence my sister read a good deal 
of Italian - she was a very good - Italian linguist, my sister, done a lot with - Italian professor there, read a lot of - art. And anyhow there was practically no subject didn't interest my sister so she - and I think they read a lot of poetry. We were t
r
emendous - family for reading aloud. Oh yes. Well my mother used to read aloud to us - a lot, when we were older, I mean - I don't remember it much before I was about nine. But - after that she used to read as loud tremendously to us. And - we sisters use
d to read aloud together, I mean, we - went through - Dante three times. Because my sister was a great Dante reader.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Would you do it in turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 In what - in turn? Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Can you remember any of the other things you read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What - what o
ne read aloud? Well, she used to read - I can remember her reading - Esmond to us, Thackeray. I think a certain amount of Dickens. And poetry - she used to read to us. And then quite a lot of Shakespeare. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You didn't do play readings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
We used to - with ourselves you see because not with her because of her not hearing. And - we ourselves used to. And then we used to - act them too. Not - not formally but just for our - well, just for my mother. But we used to do a lot of - dressing up a
nd rehearsing for it, we loved - and then - perform it just for her and my father, and - then I suppose it was a great Rostand moment, when he was very popular, because I can remember us acting l 'Aiglon, with great seal, great excitement.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Sarah Bernhardt used to didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Yes. Yes. You see that - we - yes, we'd a great thrill about all that now. In fact I think my - sister - Gwendoline, that was the eldest one - had been to see her acting l'Aiglon, hadn't ever got over it so we were always do
ing it. And we were taken, this was tremendous excitement about the first production of Chantecleer, which took place near us at San Remo. And we did go to that. And it had the famous - Guitry father in it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you enjoy it tremendously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Ye
s, I do - well it was - it was - I - enjoyed the excitement of going - to see it, there was - so much - thrill and excitement - about it. And I think I did enjoy it. It was a disappointment to me, I - on the whole I think after l'Aiglon, you know, as a pl
ay. San Remo I suppose - was rather advanced in having - I had rather grand - performances because it was a great place for hearing Paderewski, yes, I can remember we used to go to his performances there. And swooned with admiration.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was your mother very interested in music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
She loved it poor dear 'til she went deaf. She'd studied - was studying very hard with a very good - piano teacher who taught me afterwards, called Madame Haas - who was - somehow connected with - Clara Schumann - some - vague
ly related to her. And she - had been working - studying very hard with her, so she loved it and knew - a lot about it. But of course had to give it up completely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You learnt music from her in London did you, when you were in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I learned f
rom Madame Haas, yes, in London. Think she taught at the - one of the music schools where I began with her and then she taught me privately, 'til I - grew up - came out and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you have any music lessons in Yorkshire at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, I just practic
ed. And - Italy, various times there were people - I had - I had some lessons there but - after I'd really started work with Madame Haas she preferred me not to have teachers there. But we used to have a lady - come over and - who used to come over and pl
ay the violin and I used to accompany her. So that one has practice in that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was your father interested at all in music?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. I mean, you see, he loved - singing, he liked to have - singing bouts, but I mean it was - singing - Tor-roo-li-oodl
e-I-day or - and Naval songs and - Gilbert and Sullivan. Oh yes, yes, we all - we used to do a lot of yelling together, tremendous lot of singing. And he loved a - a sing-song of a sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Somebody played the piano would they and you'd sort of gather round and sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I played - generally did the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 accompaniment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 . Playing the piano. But - I know he didn't care for - music otherwise, didn't come - or at least I don't - I think very unmusically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did he care for reading aloud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 He did read t
o us - occasionally when - I think, sometimes when we've been alone at Hornby with him or - he read aloud. I think it then was chiefly - Kipling. And -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898  sort of Charles Kingsley balla}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 ds you know. Well they were evidently - oh sort of - Charles Kinglsey sort
 of - only wrote - things like - Three fishers went out to sea do you know and - men must weep - weep in the mist. Men must work and women must weep, that - ballad - balladish things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Things with a swing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. And - or - my father liked the sort
 of Kipling - ballads and - very much, and some fairly - sentimental - poetry, a lady called - Adelaide Ann Proctor. And - Ella Wheeler Wilcox. He hadn't a very - classical taste in poetry I don't think. In fact he - was not at all - he read a great deal.
 I mean he would always - had a book on hand, always read tremendously - when he was abroad at Bordigherasome time, but - no, didn't care for poetry - much poetry. Great Dickensian, he knew his Dickens backwards and forwards. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did he quite often talk about Dickens, were the characters people to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Yes, well he - he used to have tremendous quizzes - with my eldest sister who was also a great Dickensian. And - they were both - could both do very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you all read Scott a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Well I read Scott you see because - there was terrific censorship - on what one could read. Oh. That my - always enjoyed - a remark of my - a great-aunt of mine called - Lady Lansdowne, and Lord Lansdowne, who was a delicious - character and - frightfull
y kind to me always, and I used to stay with her a lot in Ireland. And I was short of a book at one time when I was there. I expect I was about seventeen. That sort of thing. So I asked her if she could supply me with a book. And she looked in her bookcas
e
 and picked one out, was going to hand it to me and then she said - oh - well perhaps not, I - oh I suppose perhaps you - oughtn't to read that. Was putting it back and then she said, oh, but it's such a wonderful book. Oh I - I think I will - give it to 
you, but read it very lightly darling won't you? And this was - Wuthering - oh not Wuth - no - Far From the Madding Crowd.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you read Hardy, was that the first Hardy that you'd read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 That was the first Hardy I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I wonder if she would have given you Jude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I think - knowing her - well she was - she wasn't at all literary, and rather simple, I don't think it would have been one she would have cared for so much. I expect she wouldn't have given me Tess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What other sort of things - how were you aware of it as a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Oh well - the - the - my mother - on - I think rather - surprisingly - censored our books a lot too, didn't allow us - was always saying we couldn't read this or that. You always had to ask - before we read a b
ook. Oh yes, and a - terrible nemesis overtook me - one time when I didn't, and I picked out - The Murders in the Rue Morgue, and didn't sleep for weeks and weeks and weeks so that cured me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you not ask because you thought she'd say no?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I expect so. Stevenson one was allowed fairly early. As I say - so I read all the whole of Scott - practically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 And Thackeray?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Thackeray - yes, eventually, but Thackeray later, but Scott - early, I mean from sort of - eightish - onwards because that
 I was allowed to - go and pick out - all - any Scott, except - the Heart of Midlothian, and - one called Fair Maid of Perth, which - I believe is very bad and as - as a result I've never read. But otherwise I read every single one including all the - ver
y bad ones. Because it was the only - one I was allowed to - pick without asking you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about the sort of children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 s books of the time, that were written specifically for children, can you remember reading them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes. I say I - I l
earnt - my - sisters - despised me very much because they considered I learnt - they learnt to read very early. And I for some reason didn't achieve it 'til I was six, so that they were very shocked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 It doesn't seem very late in life does it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Now - but it did then. Oh yes, they thought it awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Were they about four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I suppose so. And they thought that I was never going to read and I - know that I - was six and I was given - Sue - a book called Susie's Six Birthdays, as a prize, becau
se I could at last - read fluently myself. And then I - then I think I - started on an absolute orgy of - Mrs Molesworth. And - Mrs Ewing may have been a little later but - every - every Molesworth book there was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about books like the Fairchild Family, Victorian books, were they still around the place then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I suppose they were but I don't - remember reading them 'til a good deal later - I think. And more as a curiosity then I think. And - and something called the - oh yes, everyone - what was it - Eric - or Little by Little and Rosamund and the Purple Jar.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 That's Maria Edgworth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Yes, I - did read - I read those. Then there was some wonderful book called Ministering Children. Oh and a nauseating - one - over which one wept a great d
eal called - Froggy - Froggy's Little Brother. Well you know that would - is clearly a piece well worth - getting. It - there's a - some terrible stories - there's the terrible drunken father is the - root of the trouble, I think, and Froggy - is the wond
erful wordy little boy who brings up - looks after his little brother. I think he probably dies in the end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you read a book called Stubbs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Which? No. Oh no, I never read that one. Oh really, no I don't - I didn't have that one. Very famous on
e - grown ups all cried - over was something called Misunderstood wasn't there. It was again a Misunder - but I know we thought that very sloppy. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But not Froggy's little Brother, that you took quite seriously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think we thought it rather s
loppy but we did - I think we wept all the same. Then - it was a rather later stage but - I suppose the sort of - historical romances, of Stanley Heyman's and - books of that sort, I adored. I was mad about - historical novels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Were you interested in history, did you read a lot of straight history as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I was all - always - did enjoy that very much. I had a very g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 
ood - Pied}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 montese sort of maid companion really, she'd come as - the under - sort of under maid and looked after me. She had b
een a schoolteacher in her - native village. And I think must have been extremely good one, very intelligent, and I enjoyed less - I did - so I did lessons with her - reading French history and - with her. Which I enjoyed tremendously. I knew much more Fr
ench history then than - English history.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Apart from her who else taught you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Taught one? You see, mine was so scrappy I really didn't have - any - education, there was - a little - English spinster at Bordighera called Freda Cole Jones Warren, w
ho - taught one things like - really taught one from - Arthur's History of England and - in the most deadly way. And - then - spasmodic lessons from other people at - when we were in - at - home in England or classes otherwise. But never, you see, any rea
l
 governessing. From about - thirteen or something apart from - my - piedmontese, I only did lessons by correspondence classes. There was a - thing called - yes, it was in Edinburgh, St. George's classes, Edinburgh. And one - was given what to read for a f
o
rtnight, at the end of a fortnight - the papers came and you - answered them. And sent them back and then - they were marked. But of course it wasn't like having a governess who would scold you if you did badly - got bad marks. And this - you minded. You 
didn't get into trouble. But I - my mother I must say - allowed me only really to do the subjects - I liked. So that I did mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What were they besides history?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well what was called English - literature and - oddly enough grammar I rather enjoyed
. Yes. Yes. Yes, I - I enjoyed that pretty much. I - I didn't know it even existed now. And I many have done - I can't remember whether I did French, 'cos in those days - now I can't put two words together - those days I talked so much French with my pied
m
ontese - that I even used to dream in French so - it wasn't difficult, and I don't remember if I did the - may only have been - English and - history. Think perhaps geography. It was always - so - so dully taught that one wasn't very interested in it real
ly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 All about capes and bays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Yes. That sort of thing. And because my mother wasn't very good - mathematician she didn't make me do arithmetic, I know none at all. I didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 The very basic stuff I suppose you were taught by your governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I went just as - just as far as long division and no further.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You said your mother felt that you needed spoiling, what was her sort of philosophy of bringing up children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh I think it probably was fairly conventional - for the time really. And - we adored her, I mean we were frightened of her. Q}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
ite frightened of her I think. But we did adore her. And, you know, it was one - one's nightmare was I suppose from all these - sentimental Victorian books, one always thought - she was going to d
ie you know. It was one's terror. And - one wasn't you see on the - easy terms of - seeing as much of - her as - children are - now. And - I don't think one was probably expected to - when one - did come to a meal one wasn't expected to talk as much - tak
e much part and - or argue you know. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Would she talk to you though and ask you things at meals, would she sort of initiate talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Though she was - so devoted to my - she and my eld - I expect she did a great deal with my eldest sister,
 'cos she adored her and - she was so intelligent that she could talk to her - we were more put in our place - than she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Of course she would have been deaf for much more of your childhood than of your elder sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. You see, I really don't - remember her - not being deaf - at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was she really severely deaf?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh eventually, quite really. Q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 ite. Sometimes could yell down a - long tube - all those - instruments were never any good to her really, they just made noises. They were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 never - they never helped her. And - so that - I always remember her - as deaf.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Apart from the time when you read the Murders of the Rue Morgue, did you ever defy her and do things that were naughty that you remember?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh I know that I was suppo
sed to be rather naughty at one time, get into - then I was - lectured by her but I think it was if I was naughty with somebody else and it was - reported to her and then - the terrifying thing then was to be then scolded by her, that sort of thing. I don
't think she - I defied her herself. I mean not - when I was - quite young. And - even I think when}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898  I - grew up you know, not in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 tentionally, but occasionally then - lapses happen, something happens you know, that one should - shouldn't have done. Got - got 
left behind at a dance or something, by one's chaperone. Something awful that sort of thing. And - got - into trouble those ways. Or - oh yes, because there were - one did - some ways defy her - 'cos there were rules you know, you weren't to dance more th
a
n three times with the same - persons. Well I know she may have sometimes, it was partly apparently for one's own enjoyment, simply - if - that young man went away or got engaged or something - you knew nobody. I mean she - so that I can remember that - w
i
th me - you're not to dance more than three times with Mr - whoever I was - enjoying dancing with at the moment - tonight. And then she would ask one next morning, well who - who were your partners there. And I used perhaps have to own up to chiefly being
 
with Snooks, and then got into a row, so that one - I think did occasionally defy in that way. 'Til - the war when of course everything altered with a complete bang. And you know - it was a bang. The - the things one hadn't been allowed to do before. It w
as -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Like being chaperoned I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Well - when you think - I mean before - one was - wasn't allowed to go out - at any of time of day or anywhere - without a maid with one, unless - two - my sister I could - two of us - could walk - were allo
wed, great concession, to walk in certain places. Together, certain - some were barred, we might we walk down Piccadilly. We couldn't think why in those days. But we weren't. And - one bit of the - part because it was - at a certain hour just because it w
as - too fashionable - then that we had to be with somebody grown up. But - that you see 'til the war, and then within about - two months of the war - I was - fighting my way home - through - Vauxhall Bridge Road - alone - at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I believe you nursed in the war?
