at the Winterton's.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you know if your parents had had it at one time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think probable - I should think not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you think that was rather unusual for people of their kind of life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well I think - I thought it unusual to have it but - I should think perhaps it had gone out you know. By then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you have any kind of charitable visits to people in Yorkshire or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well that's why I was thinking that - and hoped that we were rather untypical because - because o
f living abroad so much that we didn't. I don't - remember then at all - having any good works of any sorts but - I suppose because we were there so little, you know, and - backwards and - forwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You didn't sort of open sales of work or do all those kinds of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Well I think for she was too deaf I suppose, my mother did some. But - I don't remember them very much. And - she did so hate - Yorkshire and really - English climate and English life you know. Well anyhow the way of life that they
 had I - it wasn't sympathetic to her, you know, it was sporting and - not at all intellectual, I think - it would have been different probably - if she'd been married to somebody different and had a sort of London life, and not been deaf. She wouldn't ha
ve had the same - she developed really I think a sort of antagonism - to England in a way. And anyhow - such a passion - for Italy. That it - swamped everything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Had she herself been there a lot as a girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, I should think not at all. Prob - I - I - not that I remember - she didn't - I don't think probably - I expect just longed to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 When you were in Yorkshire you had really very little contact with other people in the area around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Very little.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Can you remember when or how y
ou first became aware of the social position of your family? And how you sort of saw the hierarchy of English social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I don't believe I thought about it. Don't think I did. And - perhaps as you - as I say, from not - living enough in - the coun
try, English country to - see - village - village people - and - plenty enough - poor enough - country people weren't there, those days, not seeing - any of them, I - only knew - the retainers you know and you see - gamekeepers and this and that. People a
round. Gard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 ners and so on, who were employed and well off. So that - no poverty probably struck me there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 In London - I see awfully little there, and as a child - I don't remember it. I really don't remember it until I came
 out. And having the first horrors of - driving back - in the early dawn from some - wonderfully enjoyable dance and having terrible fun - and suddenly seeing - these terrible - things you thought were just - lumps of rags - on - the pavement or - benches
,
 and then seeing they were people. And I do remember develop - having - absolute horrors. And - in fact came talking to my usual - confidante, Gwendoline. Ending with practically saying that I'll never go to another dance again, it must be wrong, this and
 
that and - my sister saying it wasn't really going to - that wasn't going to cure it, we could do something else - other - take - different steps to that in trying - to console me. 'Cos the first time I remember the horror of - poverty - striking me. I th
ink I remember - I mean - younger they always say that one saw so much more drunken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
ess in London - than one does now and - do remember the sort of fight of drunks, when you see drunken fights occasionally. That sort of thing. I remember. And then - some I 
suppose - some poor people were just spoken of as so disreputable, I mean the - terrible word was tramp, you know. Keep on walking darling, don't look round, there was a tramp. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 There were a lot more tramps round then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think it was tr
emen - I should think it was a tremendous thing. And I suppose probably some of them - perhaps one them did - steal and do this and that, but obviously they looked very unkempt. But tramp was a word that - filled one with horror.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 When you started nursing presumably you came into contact with more or this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes, at once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Whereabouts were you nursing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well the first work was a tiny little - hospital they took over in Vauxhall Bridge Road. Which after all was not a very g
ood area. And - of course they - and - one immediately had - came into contact with - frightful toughs, and my favourite patient was a - a - a co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 ster, who when I asked him what made him join the army of course he said, well - some reason w had to get away
. And why had he had to get away? Well, you know, sometimes I used to - people leave things out and you take it in - you take them in for them, to save them the trouble. He was a well known burglar. And then - when we became tremendous friends he was alwa
y
s saying - next time I get a - if I can get into a store you know, I'm going to steal you yard and yards and - I'm going to pinch you yards and yards of lovely satin ribbon. So that one immediately - knew and became friends with - very very - different pe
ople.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you find that exciting at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Oh I - oh I enjoyed that tremendously, yes. Very much. It was in the - contacts with them as much - I did like nursing but - itself as - you know - from the - nursing point of view, but - it was a great de
al all the sort of friendships with the - and looking - getting on with them., patients itself - themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you ever come across any sort of aggressiveness towards you because you had a title and this kind of thing, from anybody at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes. In - you mean, those days in the hospital.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Or in other times in that early time of your life? Chip on the shoulder kind of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I don't - in the earlier - part of my life I don't remember it - very much. I mean I can remember it in the l
ast war when I was in a factory. But - noticeably absent - in the majority but - coming out occasionally, but when I was young - in the hospital I don't think I do remember it very much. Certainly not from the patients. But - it - I - it was a very small 
hospital I was in - as a matter of fact the other - probationers - were - mostly girls like me, you know, amateurs - who'd gone in. Well the sis - of course the Sisters weren't. There may have been some Sisters who had that feeling. Mostly not - I think.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You weren't made to feel you were sort of from an idle rich family or any of those kind of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 clich\'e9s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 , you didn't feel that people sort of assumed that you would have all sorts of characteristics which weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I think they may have, I can r
emember a very good - Sister that we had there, frightfully efficient and very good - very severe too - and I think she probably expected me - to be like that, and then as a matter of fact we - we got on - did me - we got on very well in the end. She quit
e got over it, but I mean - whether she just - thought any amateur or - would be bad, or because I was - a different sort of family - more so, I don't know. Didn't last anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you ever come into contact with sort of middle class and professional people very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Up to the end of the first - first war? You mean in the - what sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 People like well to do manufacturers, people who owned wool}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 en mills or ordinary clergymen and family doctors, all those sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Ah - 
well, probably family doctors. Doctors. And - clergymen, yes. Not many 'cos as I say they weren't - you see, my - parents - and - and we hated the one at Hornby. And - but there - there was a very nice - canon - at Bordighera we see quite a lot of. But - 
as I say, my mother didn't really enjoy meeting - clergy - very much. But she liked him. Otherwise she did - didn't encourage them round - a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But social class and where you were and so on, this sort of thing wasn't talked about, it was just sort of an accepted thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Yes. I mean I don't remember thinking of - doctors or - clergymen as different class - anything of that sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about the stigma attached to people in trade, do you remember that at all, hearing that talked about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
No, I don't remember - hearing it talked about but I suppose it went on 'til - after - or - even after the - first war, 'cos I think people - still - talked about - Oliver going into business instead of - the law.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 They thought this rather shocking did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I think slightly. But I don't remember my family did. I've got a feeling that he'd - some old aunts or old uncles or something - still thought it quite - not all that grand you know, I mean, wrong. But - I think it had almost died ou
t by then. And I don't remember hearing it discussed when I was - a child, I can't think what friends - I suppose banks were always respectable were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think brewers were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Brewers? Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 It wasn't something that intruded very much on you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
No. I was trying to think about the occupations of the young men - one knew do you know. And I think in those - by then it was quite all right to be in the City Certainly by the time I came out and - so before the war you see, oh very much, 
yes I mean - alone with the drunken nurse and that sort of thing, I mean the - time in Ireland I suppose, the drunken nurse and so on, and I think that was - the years that he was in Parliament you see. And - we were staying in the place in Ireland. And w
e
 saw - that's why we saw rather little of them. It explained - and also Rosemary remembered - rude remarks about him in Punch. As an MP. She said she remembered finding - coming across - an old Punch in which it said - the - MP for - Lambeth is - reported
 at the - MP for Lam - Lambeth Brixton, has had a poor }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 steeple chasing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
 and fallen on his head, this is on - it is thought that this will not make a great difference to his performance in the House. I don't think he - evidently attended much or - spoke - from what we see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 After he succeeded did he sit in the House of Lords at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I can't remember him doing - much of it. I mean I'm sure he took his - I think he - I mean he took his seat. But I expect he went - occasion - you know, for - certain important - divisions 'cos I don't remember it - in his conversation at all - really.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did your mother take an active interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, not at all really, it was purely - duty I suppose which she did, after that I don't think she took any - 
she took very little interest I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you know if he was ever active in or interested in the suffragettes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh well I do because - I'd an aunt who was - very interested, her sister was - Lady Robert Cicil, you know the - the Lord - Sir Robert
 Cecil of the League of Nations, that one, came - Lord Cecil of Chelwood. Well - his wife was my - my aunt. Aunt Millie. And she was very interested in - the suffrag}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15945211\charrsid12720898 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 tte movement, and also my mother - was friends with - the - the musician Edith Smythe. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 That's not Ethel Smythe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Eth - Ethel Smythe, I can't think why I said Edith, Ethel Smythe. She'd always known her, they were friends and she was a - militant one I mean - a marcher. No, I think my mother though - was pretty anti really. A
nd - I'm sure she was 'cos I know she had a letter from Ethel Smythe saying - you are as the miserable pet lap dog to the noble master you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you remember taking an interest yourself in political events?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I - well my elder sister I think t
ook a certain interest and used to - talk to - me about it and she always - said she would have - I mean if she'd married she'd have been quite - she was - she'd quite to like to marry a politician, that sort of thing. And I remember she was always wishin
g - saying didn't I want - Oliver to go into - politics, later this is - but I don't think I ever was - very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you remember hearing a lot of political discussion round you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well, yes, sort of hear when - you know, there were - such feuds that y
ou couldn't go to certain parties because it was a - Liberal party, and that. Some people didn't. We did because - as I say, my - we were great friends with the Asquiths, but - I mean I don't think my father would - have gone, and probably disapproved of 
u
s - going to the liberal parties. He remained - very firmly - Conservative do you know. So that I heard - yes, I did hear the veto one raging round. Otherwise as I say you think you see neither my mother or father - were - except in a crisis like that - w
ere - very interested. That's the one I remember chiefly. I mean they thought they were going to be ruined, you know, it's - nothing was ever going to be the same again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 The kind of feeling rather as there was at the time of Suez you mean in England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Where people couldn't really speak. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 And was it Lady Eden who said that the Suez Canal was flowing through her drawing room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh did she? Oh - yes, I'm sure - oh yes, it certainly did, because - I used to hear it raging between - Violet 
- Bonham Carter and - Oliver. They al - always had set to's about that. And I must say I had a view of it too - because I felt very anti-Suez, and - I did, personally. But - so we didn't - agree on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You mentioned last week about how it wasn't rig
ht to have three dances with the same young man at a ball, to dance three times with the same young man was a bad thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Well I mean it was - rather my mother's view. Yes. And I should think quite - a certain amount of mother's, not all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about sitting out dances, was that all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Oh yes, you did 'cos there was such a very - you see now I gather - or for years - one dance goes straight onto another doesn't it, there's no - silent - no break is there? But one had a long - sitting out 
- time in between each dance. So - and - so that was understood I mean you danced with somebody and - sat out 'til the next dance began.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about sitting out a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh - yes, 'cos there was - I remember - the - some young men just didn't da
nce, and when they said, will you dance with me, I'm afraid I don't dance, well you sit out and - that. But - you were -
