Yes. Oh yes. There were the sort of - calls that - I think there were some that - my mother did personally, but there were a lot that you did I think at the beginning of the - summer, the season. You were sent out in the carriage, and the c
ards were - dropped all round the - anybody who was going to give a party or had given a party - well - I remember that as a ritual. And - those cards - didn't have an - an edge was turned down, that meant that - my mother herself had called, you know, th
a
t meant it was a call to try and see the person. The other - was just a - polite - politeness. I mean like one went on doing - I don't know if people still do now - one went on doing after the war and everything - diplomatic - you know Embassies and place
s. One left cards and people may still.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I suppose a lot of these things still go on in some areas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Just leave a - you know, cards from sheer politeness but not meazning you have come to see them. There were the two sorts.
