\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you remember after Barty left and there was a new nurse got for your brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did she still look after you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think she was supposed to keep an eye on my h
ealth. That sort of thing. But not - otherwise particularly. She was - she was a hospital - hospital nurse, Ormond - she was and Ormond Street Hospital nurse who came - he was very ill when he was - quite small, my little brother. Oh some months - old, an
d she came then then they - kept her on. And she remained - as his nanny. She left her - resigned from Great Ormond Street, became his nanny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Who actually sort of looked after you at that time, would that have been a nursery governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No that's 
the one - it was then - the one who was a maid - piedmontese - maid who - been a schoolteacher, and was such a nice companion, such a good teacher. She - really - looked after and that - like made it - you know, was responsible for my clothes and - and my
 companion, but nanny - as I say, Nanny Gradage I think was meant to keep on my - health. And used to interfere a bit. She was rather a stupid woman, Nanny Gradage I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 She wasn't as nice to talk to as Barty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. No. Oh no. She was really rat
her - foolish - woman, but good at - our health, you know, so that she remained - looking after my brother while he - was rather delicate. And - I mean he was fond of her too, and she eventually married my - father's valet. I think she was having an affai
r with him, there was a slight scandal as far as I remember. But - she eventually married him. And retired and - they left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did your piedmontese come over to Hornby and London with you or did she remain there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, I think she must have remained t
here, I cannot remember her - in England at all. I think she must have always gone home. And I - awful thing is that I don't remember - when she finally left. Whether she had to go back to her parents or something, because she wasn't there - just at the e
n
d before the - war. I don't remember - she'd left sometime then. And I can't think - when, or why. And don't remember even sort of upset 'cos I was very fond of her. I should have thought I would have minded very much but I - that's lost in obscurity. She
 - left off, she did one time take on looking after - my brother, I think after Grad - Nanny Gradage had left, she took on - she looked after - Jack, quite a lot and so wasn't so much with me. Perhaps I lost touch with her a bit then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you ever remember going anywhere for a holiday, anywhere like Brighton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Oh Brighton very much, came in - Brighton came in rather a lot into our life, not so much as a holiday - because there was some - there was a doctor there called Dr. Roath - who was a - I sup
pose an orthopaedic doctor or - spinal doctor and we were - three of us, we had slight spinal curvatures, or were supposed you know, supposed to suffer from spines, and we used to go there for treatment, which we hated, he was a horrid man and it was - di
s
agreeable sort of institute where we went - and had our treatment. Doctor Roath. And we used to stay in Brighton. No, we didn't stay in the institute, we used to stay in Brighton, and attend Dr. Roath. I can remember doing it - I'm sure Gwendolen must hav
e
 gone 'cos she had the worst back. But Dorothy and I went, Olga hadn't. Dorothy and I went. And then I also remember - being there alone. Sometimes in lodgings. And another time at a - hotel. But - the rest - that - I didn't enjoy the in - institute but -
 I rather - I think we enjoyed Brighton otherwise. A lot of fun on the pier, and - the shore, seashore, riding on donkeys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 This was before you came out that you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Before? Oh when I was very small. Oh yes, I'm thinking when I - really - 
sort of six and seven. That's where I remember my port in the morning. So I - at Brighton. Yes. Then also, I forget, there was some treatment one used to be given on the pier. I can't think what that was. Whether it was - chocolate to drink, it was - some
 treat. And I think Barty used to be having her cup of tea and - I had - something else that I liked very much on the pier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did you bathe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think paddl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1012224\charrsid12720898 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 d. That's about - that's all I remember. Except I do remember a - being in a bathing - one of the - well, sort of Punch picture - bathing - cabin, the thing was drawn by a horse, so I know - I think I did - once or twice.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Was your mother there with you or were you taken by Barty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No, I don't think I - I don't remember - her ever being a
t Brigton. We went with Barty. I - that's the only seaside place I remember I think - in this - in England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Was there anything that was sort of like a holiday, somewhere where you went together with your parents or one of your parents, like people have holidays now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 No. I don't think we did at all, it was just you see changing from - England to Italy or - so on. But - no holiday - place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Your parents would go to house parties though would they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 At home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 When they were in England, they would go and stay in with people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Well, my mother very very little. Very few places, because of her - her hearing. One or two - great friends. But - oh hardly - hardly anywhere - that I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Would your father go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh he did. Oh yes, I think he - he - great many shooting - parties, coursing parties, yachting, oh very - social I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 You mentioned when you went to stay at Bowood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Would that be just on your own that you'd go and stay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes. Oh w
e went to house parties, my sisters - and I. From the moment we came out, but Bowood was different, that was relations. But - we went a lot but without - without my mother you see. I mean the moment we came out - it was a great thing, the - weekend - part
y, I mean the longer ones and - parties in Scotland and - a week, then - that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 As a child you don't remember going to stay with grandparents with your nurse or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Going - great-aunt I remember staying with. One we w
ere talking about - the household prayers, one where I remember - prayers before breakfast. That great aunt and the other great aunt Maud, you see I stayed with them quite a lot before I - came out. Then I - one of my few - friends - hadn't a great many -
 contemporary friends, you know, girl - friends, but one was - Mau}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1012224\charrsid12720898 d - Cavendish, the - Devonshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
 daughter, who was a cousin - to - really, young - little younger than me but she was a great friend, I used to stay with them. They weren't Devonshire by then,
 they - he only became Devonshire after her father was - but - they lived at a place called Hooker in Lancashire. And I used to stay with them - there, before they succeeded. And then - afterwards with them at - when he was Devonshire at Compton Place whi
c
h is a lovely place at Eastbourne. And also there's a Devonshire House there. But - I was disapproved of very much by her - her governess, Maud's governess you see because of not having a governess. She disapproved terribly that I was brought up without a
 
governess. And also that - not the conventional - religious upbringing. They were brought up in - pre-historic way I mean - even for those days. I think - Evie Devonshire - who we called Cousin Evie, she was my mother's cousin really - was - very conventi
o
nal left - the teaching and upbringing entirely to this - governess, was also - completely sort of Victorian governess - they - they had line upon line and precept upon precept, little religious books you know, like that, and - very religiously brought up
 
I suppose in the Cavendish tradition, so that she was appalled at my lack of religion you see. I'd - hadn't read the Bible, and they had to learn a collect every day do you know, a sort of - lessons of the day collect. And I had to do it with them when I 
was there. So she thought me a very bad influence. On her pupil, rather disapproved of me. And I was allowed to read the sort of books that - Maud wasn't allowed to read and - she thought it terrible, I forget what I'd read.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But you got on well with Maud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But Maud I was very fond of. She was very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Did she sort of accept her governess and her governess's sort of ideas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, did she? Oh yes, I think she hadn't - imagined any other sort of - upbringing. And I mean she was - she - was
 a very - a quite conventional household but just awful nice, jolly - girl. Who grew up a nice jolly woman almost. But - it didn't strike her I think particularly - to rebel against it. And you know and she religiously - she was - utterly - unmusical and 
- loathed playing the piano but it was considered she must learn it you know, and there she'd sit with - cold stiff fingers, hammering away, and hating it but - no question of her not - learning the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 When you were at Hornby and your sister had the German governess that your mother didn't like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 How did the governess fit in, she wasn't in the nursery, where did she eat for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think there was a thing called schoolroom meals. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 She ate with the older girls in the schoolroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
I suppose so, you see, but I really - didn't - don't even remember that governess. But I know there was - schoolroom meals - because in London there was a room where we used to have - when we - occasionally - somebody came - to teach one 
for the day - was a governess used to come occasionally, and even stay for a month or two at Hornby if we were there, and then we had meals in a separate room. Luncheon I mean. With her. And I think - the - under - most under footmen - young - youngest fo
o
tman - was called the schoolroom footman and waited on the schoolroom. And even perhaps on the - nursery sometimes, for - carried the meals for the nursery maid or something of that sort. So I - one knew the - under-footman, he was a - a friend and probab
ly - one knew him to talk to and run about - you know, he'd do kind things for one and - play with one, carry one upstairs when one's legs ached, that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What did he call you when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh I think lady. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What would Barty have called you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh Moira.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 She would have called you by your own name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 But the other servants would have given you your title?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I should think the nursery maid called one - Moira. That I don't remember about the nursery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1012224\charrsid12720898 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 maid, and - the others, but certainly the - not the - footman I think would have called - certainly called one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 How would they have addressed your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Your Grace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Both of them were addressed as your Grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Do you remember if the cook was given the title of Mrs whether she was married or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Oh yes. I think that went on for ages. I mean went on in - Oliver and I my day. One we had for longest was somebody called Mrs. Wilson. Certainly that was. And - and the nurse you see, was Mrs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 So Barty was Mrs Flambard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 
Yes. That I think died out very slowly 'cos I remember being - surprised when - Olive - Arthur - our nanny - for my children - when she said she preferred to be called - Miss Grace instead of - not Mrs Grace. I was-quite surprised. It was 19 - 20.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 And that was the first time you'd come across that change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 I think they all - I thought they were all Mrs before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 What about the footman and the housemaids, what were they called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 By their -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Surnames for first names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Oh Christian names, housemaids. And - footmen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Footmen by Christian names too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1054659 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Were there any servants who were called by just their surnames?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5195713 ML  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2701124\charrsid12720898 Yes, I mean the - butler would be, and then -
